{"parse":{"title":"The Falcon (character)","pageid":1339145,"revid":848152112,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the fictional detective. For the comic book superhero, see <a href=\"/wiki/Falcon_(comics)\" title=\"Falcon (comics)\">Falcon (comics)</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em;border-spacing: 2px 5px;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background: #DEDEE2;\">Gay Stanhope Falcon/Gay Laurence/Tom Laurence/Michael \"Mike\" Waring</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">First appearance</th><td>\n<i>Gay Falcon</i></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Created by</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Arlen\" title=\"Michael Arlen\">Michael Arlen</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Portrayed by</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/George_Sanders\" title=\"George Sanders\">George Sanders</a> (film) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Conway\" title=\"Tom Conway\">Tom Conway</a> (film) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/Barry_Kroeger\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Barry Kroeger\">Barry Kroeger</a> (radio) <br />  James Meighan (radio) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/Les_Tremayne\" title=\"Les Tremayne\">Les Tremayne</a> (radio) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/Les_Damon\" title=\"Les Damon\">Les Damon</a> (radio) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/George_O._Petrie\" title=\"George O. Petrie\">George Petrie</a> (radio) <br /><a href=\"/wiki/John_Calvert_(magician)\" title=\"John Calvert (magician)\">John Calvert</a> (film) <br /> <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_McGraw\" title=\"Charles McGraw\">Charles McGraw</a> (television)</td></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background: #DEDEE2;\">Information</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Gender</th><td>\nMale</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td>\nPrivate detective</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:152px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg/150px-George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"181\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg/225px-George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"255\" data-file-height=\"308\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:George_Sanders_in_Ghost_and_Mrs_Muir_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/George_Sanders\" title=\"George Sanders\">George Sanders</a>, original star of <i>The Falcon</i> film series</div></div></div><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:152px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg/150px-Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"169\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg/225px-Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/99/Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"274\" data-file-height=\"309\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tom_Conway_in_Grand_Central_Murder_trailer_headcrop.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sanders' brother, <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Conway\" title=\"Tom Conway\">Tom Conway</a>, replaced Sanders as The Falcon partway through the series</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Gay Stanhope Falcon</b> (later known in film and radio as <b>The Falcon</b>) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Fictional_character\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Fictional character\">fictional character</a> created in 1940 by <a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Arlen\" title=\"Michael Arlen\">Michael Arlen</a>. Falcon made his first appearance in Arlen's short story \"Gay Falcon\", which was first published in 1940 in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Town_%26_Country_(magazine)\" title=\"Town &amp; Country (magazine)\">Town &amp; Country</a></i> magazine. Falcon is characterized as a freelance adventurer and troubleshooter - a man who makes his living \"keeping his mouth shut and engaging in dangerous enterprises.\"  \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Film_appearances\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Film appearances</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Film_series\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Film series</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Film_appearances\">Film appearances</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Falcon_(character)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Film appearances\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Falcon was quickly brought to the screen by <a href=\"/wiki/RKO\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"RKO\">RKO</a> - <a href=\"/wiki/1941_in_film\" title=\"1941 in film\">1941</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Gay_Falcon\" title=\"The Gay Falcon\">The Gay Falcon</a></i> redefined the character as a suave <a href=\"/wiki/England\" title=\"England\">English</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Gentleman_detective\" title=\"Gentleman detective\">gentleman detective</a> with a weakness for beautiful women. The film was intended to establish a suitable replacement character for <a href=\"/wiki/Leslie_Charteris\" title=\"Leslie Charteris\">Leslie Charteris</a>' <a href=\"/wiki/Simon_Templar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Simon Templar\">Simon Templar</a> (aka The Saint, hero of a popular RKO film series). To that end, <a href=\"/wiki/George_Sanders\" title=\"George Sanders\">George Sanders</a> (star of <i>The Saint</i> series) was cast. Though Gay Falcon was the character's name in Arlen's original story, the character was renamed Gay Laurence for the film. (The surname was spelled \"Lawrence\" in subsequent films.) Thus \"The Falcon\" became an alias, or nickname (\u00e0 la \"The Saint\"). In later outings, in various media, the character had a variety of \"real names,\" while still being known as The Falcon. Neither in films nor on radio was the nickname ever explained. \n</p><p>Sanders appeared in the first three Falcon films, which followed the \"Saint\" pattern so closely that author Charteris sued RKO for plagiarism (Charteris pokes fun at The Falcon in his 1943 novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Saint_Steps_In\" title=\"The Saint Steps In\">The Saint Steps In</a></i>, with a character making a <a href=\"/wiki/Metafiction\" title=\"Metafiction\">metafictional</a> reference to the Falcon being \"a bargain-basement imitation\" of The Saint.)<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Sanders, tired of B leads, bowed out of the series in <i>The Falcon's Brother</i> (1942). The Falcon's brother, Tom Lawrence, became the new Falcon, and was portrayed by Sanders' actual brother, <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Conway\" title=\"Tom Conway\">Tom Conway</a>. After <i>The Falcon's Brother</i>, Conway starred in nine further Falcon films through 1946, almost always with a wisecracking sidekick, portrayed variously by <a href=\"/wiki/Edward_Brophy\" title=\"Edward Brophy\">Edward Brophy</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Allen_Jenkins\" title=\"Allen Jenkins\">Allen Jenkins</a> (who played the same role in the first three Sanders films), <a href=\"/wiki/Don_Barclay_(actor)\" title=\"Don Barclay (actor)\">Don Barclay</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Cliff_Edwards\" title=\"Cliff Edwards\">Cliff Edwards</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Vince_Barnett\" title=\"Vince Barnett\">Vince Barnett</a>. \n</p><p>An oft-used gimmick in the Falcon series was to tack \"teaser\" epilogues onto the ends of films. In a teaser, a previously unseen character would approach the Falcon, usually in  comic fashion, and signal the title and locale of his next movie. A teaser rarely had anything to do with the plot of the upcoming film, since that film had not yet been produced. \n</p><p>The Falcon character was revived for three more films, all made in 1948, starring <a href=\"/wiki/John_Calvert_(magician)\" title=\"John Calvert (magician)\">John Calvert</a> and changing the character's name to \"Michael Waring\", but these were unsuccessful. The character went on to appear (as Michael Waring) in <a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_(radio)\" title=\"The Falcon (radio)\">radio</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Television\" title=\"Television\">television</a> - <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_McGraw\" title=\"Charles McGraw\">Charles McGraw</a> portrayed the Falcon in the 39-episode <a href=\"/wiki/Broadcast_syndication\" title=\"Broadcast syndication\">syndicated</a> <a href=\"/wiki/TV_Series\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"TV Series\">television series</a> <i>Adventures of the Falcon</i> (1954-55).<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Film_series\">Film series</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Falcon_(character)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Film series\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Starring <a href=\"/wiki/George_Sanders\" title=\"George Sanders\">George Sanders</a> as Gay Lawrence\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Gay_Falcon\" title=\"The Gay Falcon\">The Gay Falcon</a></i> (1941)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/A_Date_with_the_Falcon\" title=\"A Date with the Falcon\">A Date with the Falcon</a></i> (1942)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_Takes_Over\" title=\"The Falcon Takes Over\">The Falcon Takes Over</a></i> (1942) (based on <a href=\"/wiki/Raymond_Chandler\" title=\"Raymond Chandler\">Raymond Chandler</a>'s <i><a href=\"/wiki/Farewell,_My_Lovely\" title=\"Farewell, My Lovely\">Farewell, My Lovely</a></i>)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon%27s_Brother\" title=\"The Falcon&#39;s Brother\">The Falcon's Brother</a></i> (1942)</li></ul></li>\n<li>Featuring Sanders and <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Conway\" title=\"Tom Conway\">Tom Conway</a> as the Lawrence brothers. Gay is murdered and Tom Lawrence, his brother, becomes The Falcon\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_Strikes_Back\" title=\"The Falcon Strikes Back\">The Falcon Strikes Back</a></i> (1943)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_in_Danger\" title=\"The Falcon in Danger\">The Falcon in Danger</a></i> (1943)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_and_the_Co-eds\" title=\"The Falcon and the Co-eds\">The Falcon and the Co-eds</a></i> (1943)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_Out_West\" title=\"The Falcon Out West\">The Falcon Out West</a></i> (1944)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_in_Mexico\" title=\"The Falcon in Mexico\">The Falcon in Mexico</a></i> (1944)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_in_Hollywood\" title=\"The Falcon in Hollywood\">The Falcon in Hollywood</a></i> (1944)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon_in_San_Francisco\" title=\"The Falcon in San Francisco\">The Falcon in San Francisco</a></i> (1945)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon%27s_Alibi\" title=\"The Falcon&#39;s Alibi\">The Falcon's Alibi</a></i> (1946)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Falcon%27s_Adventure\" title=\"The Falcon&#39;s Adventure\">The Falcon's Adventure</a></i> (1946)</li></ul></li>\n<li>Starring <a href=\"/wiki/John_Calvert_(magician)\" title=\"John Calvert (magician)\">John Calvert</a> as Michael Waring\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Devil%27s_Cargo\" title=\"Devil&#39;s Cargo\">Devil's Cargo</a></i> (1948)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Appointment_with_Murder\" title=\"Appointment with Murder\">Appointment with Murder</a></i> (1948)</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Search_for_Danger\" title=\"Search for Danger\">Search for Danger</a></i> (1949)</li></ul></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Falcon_(character)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Charteris, Leslie. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Saint_Steps_In\" title=\"The Saint Steps In\">The Saint Steps In</a></i> (1943) (1980 Charter Books edition, p. 153)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047704/\">https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047704/</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://ctva.biz/US/Adventure/Falcon.htm\">http://ctva.biz/US/Adventure/Falcon.htm</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.thrillingdetective.com/falcon.html\">http://www.thrillingdetective.com/falcon.html</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Falcon_(character)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thrillingdetective.com/falcon.html\">The Falcon</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thrillingdetective.com/non_fiction/e010.html\">On the Trail of Drexel Drake's Falcon: An On-going Investigation by Frank Derato</a></li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"The_Falcon\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks hlist collapsible collapsed navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"2\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:The_Falc